@node Compiling
@chapter Compiling

@cindex compiling
@cindex F9
@cindex compiler message format
@cindex gcc
@cindex make

xwpe integrates with external compilers through a compile-edit-debug
cycle.  The compiler is configured per language (by file extension) and
xwpe parses compiler output to jump to errors in the source code.

This chapter was tested on 2026-05-28 with xwpe 1.6.1 against GCC 15.2,
G++ 15.2, GFortran 15.2, Free Pascal 3.2.2, OpenJDK javac 25.0.3,
Perl 5.40.1, and Python 3.13.12.

@section The build cycle

@cindex build cycle
@cindex Alt-F9
@cindex Ctrl-F9

The build cycle uses three commands, each building on the previous:

@table @kbd
@item Alt-F9 (Compile)
Compile the current file only.  xwpe invokes the configured compiler
with @code{-c -o @var{file}.o @var{file}.c} (or equivalent for other
languages).  Only files modified since the last compilation are
recompiled.

@item F9 (Make)
Recompile all modified files and link the executable.  This is the
most common command.

@item Ctrl-F9 (Run)
Build the executable and then run it.  Program arguments can be set
via @samp{Run @result{} Arguments} (@kbd{Alt-R A}).
@end table

After compilation, errors appear in the Message Window.  Use
@kbd{Alt-R N} (Next Error) and @kbd{Alt-R P} (Previous Error) to
navigate between errors.  The cursor jumps to the error location in
the source code.

@section Configuring the compiler

@cindex compiler configuration
@cindex Options menu

The compiler is configured via @samp{Options @result{} Compiler}
(@kbd{Alt-O C}).  Each language is identified by its file extension
(e.g.@: @file{.c} for C, @file{.cpp} for C++).

Settings per language:
@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{Compiler}: path to the compiler (e.g.@: @code{/usr/bin/gcc}).
@item @strong{Compiler Options}: flags passed to the compiler
(e.g.@: @code{-Wall -g}).
@item @strong{Loader Options}: flags passed to the linker
(e.g.@: @code{-lm}).
@item @strong{Executable Name}: name of the output binary
(default: @code{a.out}).
@item @strong{Compiler Style}: @code{GNU} (default) or @code{other}
(custom message-string format).
@end itemize

@section Language support

@cindex language support

xwpe selects the compiler automatically based on the file extension.
The following table summarises tested language support.

@subsection First-class support (GNU error format)

@multitable @columnfractions .12 .15 .15 .20 .38
@headitem Language @tab Compiler @tab Extension @tab Error format @tab Notes
@item C @tab gcc @tab .c @tab @code{file:line:col: error:} @tab
  Default configuration.  Tested with GCC 15.2.0.
@item C++ @tab g++ @tab .cpp @tab @code{file:line:col: error:} @tab
  Same error format as gcc.
@item Fortran @tab gfortran @tab .f90 @tab @code{file:line:col:} @tab
  GNU-compatible format.  Tested with GFortran 15.2.0.
@item Java @tab javac @tab .java @tab @code{file:line: error:} @tab
  GNU-compatible.  Tested with OpenJDK 25.0.3.
  @strong{Limitation}: javac does not accept @code{-c -o} flags.
  xwpe assumes all compilers use @code{-c -o}; a wrapper script is
  needed (@pxref{Compiling,,Java workaround}).
@end multitable

@subsection Partial support (non-GNU format)

@multitable @columnfractions .12 .15 .15 .58
@headitem Language @tab Compiler @tab Extension @tab Notes
@item Pascal @tab fpc @tab .pas @tab
  Error format: @code{file(line,col) Fatal: msg}.  Does not match
  GNU format.  Requires @code{CMPSWTCH=other} with a custom
  message-string in the project file.  Tested with FPC 3.2.2.
@item Perl @tab perl -c @tab .pl @tab
  Error format: @code{at file line N}.  Does not match GNU format.
  xwpe cannot parse Perl errors natively.
@item Python @tab python3 @tab .py @tab
  Error format varies (SyntaxError, tracebacks).  Does not match
  GNU format.  xwpe cannot parse Python errors natively.
@end multitable

@subsection Other GNU-compatible compilers

Any compiler that produces errors in the @code{file:line: message}
format will work with xwpe's default @code{GNU} compiler style.
This includes: Rust (@command{rustc}), Go (@command{go build}),
Scala, and many others.

@section Java workaround
@anchor{Java workaround}

@cindex Java
@cindex javac
@cindex wrapper script

@command{javac} does not accept @code{-c} and @code{-o} flags.
To use Java with xwpe, create a wrapper script:

@example
#!/bin/sh
# Save as ~/bin/javac-wrapper
# Strips -c and -o flags that xwpe passes
args=""
skip_next=0
for arg in "$@@"; do
    if [ "$skip_next" = 1 ]; then
        skip_next=0
        continue
    fi
    case "$arg" in
        -c) continue ;;
        -o) skip_next=1; continue ;;
        *) args="$args $arg" ;;
    esac
done
exec javac $args
@end example

Then configure xwpe to use @code{~/bin/javac-wrapper} as the compiler
for @file{.java} files.

@section Custom message-string format

@cindex message-string
@cindex CMPSWTCH
@cindex error parsing

When @code{CMPSWTCH} is set to @code{other} in the project file,
xwpe uses a custom message-string to parse compiler output.

Available placeholders:

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Placeholder @tab Meaning
@item @code{$@{FILE@}} @tab Filename containing the error.
@item @code{$@{LINE[+-N]@}} @tab Line number (optional offset N).
@item @code{$@{COLUMN[+-N]@}} @tab Column number (optional offset N).
@item @code{$@{COLUMN=BEFORE[+-N]@}} @tab Column is position before a string.
@item @code{$@{COLUMN=AFTER[+-N]@}} @tab Column is position after a string.
@item @code{$@{?N:STR@}} @tab Warning detection (N = column or @code{*},
STR = string to match).
@item @code{\n} @tab Line break for multi-line messages.
@end multitable

@subsection Example: Free Pascal

@example
CMPSWTCH = other
# FPC format: file(line,col) Fatal: message
MESSAGE = $@{FILE@}($@{LINE@},$@{COLUMN@})*
@end example

@section Known issues

@cindex compiler bugs

@strong{Error message parsing crash (v1.6.1)}: after compilation,
xwpe may crash (SIGSEGV) when parsing GCC 15's multi-line error
output.  The compiler runs correctly and produces valid output, but
the message parser encounters an issue with the new error format
that includes context lines with carets and pipe characters.  This
is being investigated (upstream bug).

